'''Yagawa Shrine''' (やがわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kōnan-chō Morijiri|Q86735490|WD=Q86735490|1=Kōnan-chō Morijiri}}, {{ill|lt=Kōka|Q847584|WD=Q847584|1=Kōka, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The principal deities are {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}} and Yagawa-e-hime-no-Mikoto<ref>{{Cite web|和書|title=Yagawa Shrine|url=http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=613|website=|accessdate=2019-10-24|publisher=Shiga Prefecture Shrine Office}}</ref>. Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto is revered as a deity of industry and long healthy life; Yagawa-e-hime-no-Mikoto as a deity for mastery of arts and fulfillment of wishes.

Yagawa-e-hime-no-Mikoto is also written as Yagawae-hime / Yagawae-hime. In the genealogy of Ōkuninushi in the {{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|WD=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}, there is a passage: "{{ill|lt=Kuninintomi-no-Kami|Q48759713|WD=Q48759713|1=Kuninotoshimi-no-Kami}} married {{ill|lt=Ashinadaka-no-Kami|Q55533749|WD=Q55533749|1=Ashinataka-no-Kami}} (also called Yagawae-hime), and their child was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hayamika-no-Takesawaya-jinumi-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}." Also, in the {{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}} section of the Kojiki, Miyanushi Yagawae-hime appears as one of the emperor's consorts.

=== History ===
Shrine tradition says it was founded in the {{ill|lt=Tenpyō|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} era, during construction of {{ill|lt=Shigaraki-no-Miya|Q262438|WD=Q262438|1=Shigaraki Palace}} by {{ill|lt=Emperor Shōmu|Q349263|WD=Q349263|1=Emperor Shōmu}}. In the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}},' it appears first among eight shrines of Kōka District, {{ill|lt=Ōmi Province|Q843882|WD=Q843882|1=Ōmi Province}}, and is listed as a small shrine. A 1337 source from the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|WD=Q264012|1=Nanboku-chō period}} records it as "Soma-no-Kawa-no-Miya," and in the medieval period it gathered support from local warrior-landholders as the sōsha of Ikebara Soma-shō<ref name=":0" />. In the {{ill|lt=Sengoku period|Q204023|WD=Q204023|1=Sengoku period}}, it was used as a meeting place of the {{ill|lt=Kōka-gun Chūsō|Q85882491|WD=Q85882491|1=Kōka ikki}}, functioning as a site strengthening regional cohesion<ref name=":1" />. After the decline of Kōka groups in the {{ill|lt=Kōka-yure|Q6455112|WD=Q6455112|1=Kōga-ryū}} of {{ill|lt=1585|Q6736|WD=Q6736|1=1585}}, ritual structure changed. In {{ill|lt=1652|Q6962|WD=Q6962|1=1652}}, among ujiko villages, 9 villages became ujiko of Shingū Shrine ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kōnan-chō Shinjī|1=UNKNOWN}}), 6 villages became ujiko of Hiyoshi Shrine ({{ill|lt=Minakuchi-chō Sandaiji|Q86735520|WD=Q86735520|1=Minakuchi-chō Sandaiji}}), and 7 villages (Morijiri, Fukagawa, Hietani, Kuzuraki, Terashō, Sugitani, Shiono) remained ujiko (Yagawa Hongō / Yagawa 7 villages), while another 15 villages were called external ujiko<ref name=":0" />. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was a revered shrine of {{ill|lt=Minakuchi Domain|Q10863504|WD=Q10863504|1=Minakuchi Domain}}. In October {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|WD=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} 13 ({{ill|lt=1842|Q7625|WD=Q7625|1=1842}}), the "Kōka Disturbance" ({{ill|lt=Ōmi Tenpō Uprising|Q11638484|WD=Q11638484|lt=Tenpō uprising|1=Tenpō uprising}}) occurred at this shrine precinct, where tens of thousands of farmers gathered and rose against shogunate land survey policy.

Before Meiji it was called Yagawa Daimyōjin and was a broad-area village guardian shrine with a wide ujiko sphere<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Kōka City History Vol.8 Kōka City Encyclopedia|date=2016年12月12日|year=2016|publisher=Kōka City|pages=171-172}}</ref>. Rituals were carried out under {{ill|lt=shinbutsu shūgō|Q2279088|WD=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}} by Yagawadera Seijō-in, the shrine's {{ill|lt=jingūji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}} (now extinct)<ref name=":0" />.

=== National historic site ===
Precincts - designated as a national historic site as one of the {{ill|lt=Kōka-gun Chūsō|Q85882491|WD=Q85882491|lt=Kōka-gun Chūsō site group|1=Kōka ikki}}<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|author=Kōka City|year=2009|title=Understanding the real figure of Kōka warriors who raced through the Sengoku period|url=http://www.city.koka.lg.jp/secure/6711/2009_0601_p02_03.pdf|journal=Kōhō Aikōka|volume=June 1 issue|page=}}</ref>.

=== Cultural properties ===
=== Prefecture-designated cultural properties ===
* Rōmon gate - said to have been donated in thanks for rainmaking fulfilled for 50 villages in {{ill|lt=Yamabe District|Q1130739|WD=Q1130739|1=Yamabe District, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} (northern {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}). Originally two-storied, but said to have lost the upper story to weather. Built in {{ill|lt=1482|Q6633|WD=Q6633|1=1482}}<ref name=":0" />.
* Paper, light-color paintings "Immortals with game board books" and "Landscape" - by {{ill|lt=Yokoi Kinkoku|Q3122882|WD=Q3122882|1=Yokoi Kinkoku}}.

=== City-designated cultural properties ===
* Honden - sangen-sha nagare-zukuri with steel-sheet roof. Rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1755|Q7627|WD=Q7627|1=1755}} by Takagi Tajima, a carpenter from Hachiman<ref name=":0" />.
* Stone arched bridge (taiko-bashi) - built in {{ill|lt=1671|Q7610|WD=Q7610|1=1671}}. Oldest stone arched bridge in Kōka<ref>{{Cite book|title=Kōka City History Vol.8 Kōka City Encyclopedia|date=2016年12月12日|year=2016|publisher=Kōka City|page=389}}</ref> and largest<ref name=":0" />.
* Wooden male deity statue - Heian-period work.

=== Other ===
* Wooden female deity statue - Heian-period work<ref name=":0" />.

